1. e4
{ Before we start the intro - an important thing:  This course doesn't contain any Anti-Sicilians for White. It is a full repertoire for Black against 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6. All of the other tries for White such as Alapin, Morra, Grand Prix etc. will be covered in the separate course. More about my decision here:   @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/discussion/thread/167985/my-upcoming-four-knights-sicilian-course/@@LinkEnd@@  
Firstly, I would like to thank you for purchasing this course. It is the fruit of my latest research and with the 2nd part will cover Black's full repertoire against 1.e4.  
If I were forced to identify my biggest problem with the opening repertoire, I would instantly reply 'Black vs 1.e4'. I have never had any issues with the White colour and also, against 1. d4, 1. c4, 1. Nf3 etc. I've always gone for the King's Indian Defence. However, against 1.e4 I tried no less than 7 different setups throughout the last 10-15 years. I think that finding the right opening vs White's most active first move is a major challenge - especially nowadays. }
1... c5
{ While I keep some options such as Accelerated Dragon or Alekhine as surprising weapons, I decided that if I want to improve, I need to start playing something that at least resembles the main lines. I had some kind of a brainstorm with myself and I was wondering which setups with White I love playing and I tried to look for a similar opening with the Black pieces. When e3 English came into my mind, I knew that some sort of Sicilian with ... e6 will be my choice. }
2. Nf3
{ As I have mentioned in the intro, this course will be only about the open sicilian. }
2... e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ This is the starting position of the Four Knights Sicilian  (which I will also call the Four Horsemen)  . Black's position is very active and full of dynamism. Here are some promises from me:  1   You will ALWAYS have active pieces. There will be some scenarios where our c8-Bishop might be a bad piece, but you will ALWAYS manage to exchange it. This is a promise. Black's basic plan in the diagram position is to play ... Bb4 and put immediate pressure on White's centre.  2   In the lines that I recommend, you will never be left with the weak d5-square as in the Sveshnikov or some lines of the Najdorf. We will either keep the pawn on e6 or will manage to play ... d7 - d5 in one move.  3   All setups with f3 + Be3 or with Bc4 are dubious at best for our opponent, which means no vicious attacks on our King.  4   There will be only a few lines with the opposite castling, but it will usually mean problems for White - no attacks on our King!  5   Vast majority of lines is based on understanding and planning more than memorizing and calculating. Of course, there will be some exceptions - especially the 7.Bf4 chapter - but most of the time, you will manage to outplay your opponent by memorizing plans, not exact moves.  6   The Anti-Sicilians will be much easier to learn and play than after 2... Nc6 or 2... d6 = no Rossolimo and against both the Closed Sicilian and the Grand Prix Attack we will manage to play a quick ... e6 and ... d5.  7   It is a perfect repertoire for rapid and blitz. Note that White will usually be ready for the Najdorf, Sveshnikov or Dragon, but in many cases, your opponent won't be familiar with any line vs Four Horsemen  (or may be familiar with a line but without any plans in mind)  .  8   There are only a few sources that cover this line from Black's perspective, and I also don't agree with many of points from them. That means that my lines are quite fresh and they see the daylight for the first time. That means that your opponent has no chance to be prepared for them.  9   Last but not least, there will be a few variations where White has a MARGINAL advantage, but no more than that. In all cases, we will have active counterplay, even if we are slightly worse.  I must admit that my experience with this system is quite beginnerish  (now it is a word)  and I have played it for not more than 2 months, but I am fully in love with the opening. For the first time in my life, I can't await my opponent to go for 1.e4 and I know I am fully prepared - especially for the Open Sicilian. I hope that you might get the same state of mind after learning this course and I wish you to have even 10% of joy that I have when playing it! Good luck with the course, good luck with learning and have some easy points!  Kamil Plichta, Koszalin 24.02.2020 }
