1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ This is the starting position of the so-called Four Knights Sicilian. It is by far less popular than the Najdorf, Sveshnikov, Dragon or Taimanov, but I think we will see a big boost of popularity of this system  (one of the reasons hopefully being an enormous amount of sales of this course !)  . The line is not very popular because there is a common belief that White has a very easy path to an easy advantage and Black can't do anything about that. I hope to convince you that it is not true and all that White can count on is the slightest of advantages in several lines. I've mentioned in the introduction why I have a huge fondness for this system so let's proceed with our learning, shall we ? The last thing to add is that in this chapter we will take a look at White's rare 6th moves. }
6. g3
{ In my opinion the only dangerous sideline - or at least the one that asks some questions. Not hard ones, but still - questions. White's idea is to just put the Bishop on g2, castle short and go on with his life claiming that he has a nice grip on the centre. }
6... Bb4
{ This is the move that you will see as a recurring theme throughout this course. Black actively develops the Bishop and in many cases will continue with ... d5 - not in this case, but in many positions this will be our standard plan. }
7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O d6
{ With the Bishop on g2 we should refrain from pushing ... d5 as the isolated pawn on d5 would be a long-term target. I think we can get a good game by playing more slowly this time. }
9. Nde2
{ The most popular continuation preventing ... Nxd4 and putting some pressure on the d6-pawn. }
9... a6
{ This thematic move covers b5 and frees the a7-square for the Bishop. } 10. h3
Bc5
{ Black's main plan is to play ... b5 followed by ... Bb7 but watch out for the e5 trick from White! We can always support our plan by playing ... Qc7 and/or ... Rb8. }
