Ne4
{ The most dangerous system favoured by many of the top players. Together with 6. Ndb5 Bb4 7. a3 I consider it to be the most dangerous weapon against our setup. White's plan is to play a well-timed c4 and push all of our pieces back while using the d6-square. Things are however far from simple. The e5-pawn is a target and White will be often forced to defend it by f4. Black has many different setups possible but I decided to go for a rather rare and original one. }
8... Bb7
{ Only the 4th most popular move but I really like it. Black's idea is to play ... c5 opening up the Bishop and preparing an attack on the d6-pawn by playing ... Qc7. }
9. c4
{ A smaller brother of 9. Be2. White doesn't care about development and wants to punish us immediately for our slow play. }
9... Nb4 10. c5
{ This is what we call an outpost ! The d6-square is going to be in White's hands and the Bishop on b7 is firmly blocked. So what is our idea now ? We will provoke White to weaken the position even further and then we will claim that White overextended himself and we have good counterplay. }
10... Qb8
{ This is a key move that secures Black good chances. We provoke White to commit to some sort of a weakness. }
11. Nd6+ { This might be the most tempting move so let's check it first. }
11... Bxd6 12. cxd6 a5
{ I think that in this line it is better to refrain from ... Ba6. Let's see why I don't like two of more obvious moves for Black:   12...Ba6 !?  is interesting but after  13.Qg4  Black doesn't have  13...Kf8  due to  14.Bxa6  Nxa6  15.O-O  We see that the fact that the c-pawn doesn't hang makes a huge difference.   12...Ba6 !?  13.Qg4  forces Black to go  13...Nd3+  14.Bxd3  Bxd3  15.Qxg7  Qb4+  16.Bd2  Qe4+  17.Kd1  O-O-O.  I think that Black has almost enough compensation but I have a feeling that it is always possible for White to press here while I am not fully convinced that it works well for Black. Still, a possible line to try in practice.   12...O-O  is the other idea but I think it is impractical due to  13.Bh6 !  By playing 12... a5 Black defends the Knight and prepares ... Ba6 without committing anything. Also, it might sound stupid but it frees the a7-square for the Black Queen ! }
13. a3
{ 13.Qg4?  Qa7!  is a surprising but a very strong resource with the point being that  14.Qxg7  runs into  14...O-O-O  and Black's position is already dominant. }
13... Nd5 14. Qg4 Kf8
{ Black's next move is ... Ba6 against most of White's options. } 15. h4
{ It is important to see that White's plan of h5 or Rh3 - g3 is quite dangerous and we have to react immediately postponing ... Ba6 for later. }
15... h5 16. Qe4 f5
{ It is necessary to play this move immediately. If we waste a move on something like  16...a4  , then White will play  17.Rh3  and  17...f5  can be answered with  18.exf6  Nxf6  19.Rf3  with a serious advantage for White.  The biggest point of ... f5 is that we need to get our King to the 7th rank to bring the h8-Rook into the game. ... Ba6 comes next and the King will be very safe on f7. The fact that White doesn't have a Knight to jump into g5 is quite significant. }
