1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Ndb5 Bb4 7. a3
{ Finally, after at least two trips to Mordor and back, we are back to Shire, where the grass is green and life peaceful. This is how I would compare the previous chapters with this and next two. 7. a3 is by far White's most popular move and is widely considered to be a move that gives White an easy advantage. I agree with the part that there are lines where Black's position will be SLIGHTLY inferior but these can be counted on the fingers of one hand. And as I've said, White will be only marginally better. }
7... Bxc3+
{ We are forced to give up the dark-squared Bishop but we will have other positive aspects of our position. }
8. Nxc3 d5
{ This is Black's basic idea. We lost the dark-squared Bishop but as usual, our Knights are on the perfect squares and we immediately start challenging White's centre.   It is necessary to play this move immediately, since  8...O-O?!  runs into  9.Qd6!  and it is awkward to carry through the  ...d5 break  (.) }
9. Bd3
{ This is around 10 times less popular than 9. exd5 which is the topic of the final two chapters. White doesn't commit to exd5 yet and just develops the Bishop. The disadvantage is that we will be able to push the pawn to d4. }
9... d4
{ I don't like  9...dxe4  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Bxe4  Qxd1+  12.Kxd1  which is playable but extremely hard to push for a win with Black. White enjoys a pair of Bishops for free and I consider this position to be very impractical. }
10. Ne2 e5
{ Black managed to build a nice pawn duo in the centre. Also, the fact that we exchanged the dark-squared Bishop is quite beneficial since these pawns are on the dark squares and the Bishop would be blocked by them. }
11. O-O O-O
{ This is more or less the starting position of the 9. Bd3 line. White enjoys a pair of Bishops but Black has some space advantage. One plan for Black to remember is that whenever White goes for f4 we will play ... exf4 followed by planting one of the Knights on e5 - most probably the f6-Knight. Our preferred way should be ... Ng4 - e5 because sometimes we might jump into e3 from g4. The alternative way is ... Nd7 - e5. }
12. Ng3 { White prepares to play f4. } 12... Be6
{ ... Nd7 is our next move to prepare ... exf4 followed by ... Nde5 as a response to f4. }
13. f4 exf4 { As I've said, this is Black's basic idea in this line. } 14. Bxf4
Ng4
{ Even stronger than 14... Nd7. Black not only wants to play ... Nge5 but ... Ne3 is an option that White has to parry. }
15. Nf5 Nge5
{ Black will follow up with ... f6 and ... Rc8 with a complicated position. White has a pair of Bishops but Black has a perfect Knight on e5. }
